WEBVTT

00:22.340 --> 00:25.140
CHAPTER IV.

00:27.620 --> 00:36.800
As with our colleges, so with a hundred modern improvements. There is an illusion about them,

00:37.120 --> 00:44.060
there is not always a positive advance. The devil goes on exacting compound interest to the last,

00:44.520 --> 00:51.860
for his early share and numerous succeeding investments in them. Our inventions are want

00:51.860 --> 00:59.560
to be pretty toys, which distract our attention from serious things. They are but improved means

00:59.560 --> 01:08.220
to an unimproved end, an end which it was already but too easy to arrive at, as railroads lead to

01:08.220 --> 01:15.100
Boston or New York. We are in great haste to construct a magnetic telegraph from Maine to

01:15.100 --> 01:25.180
Texas, but Maine and Texas, it may be, have nothing important to communicate. Either is

01:25.180 --> 01:31.520
in such a predicament as the man who was earnest to be introduced to a distinguished deaf woman,

01:32.380 --> 01:37.440
but when he was presented and one end of her ear trumpet was put into his hand,

01:39.620 --> 01:49.260
as if the main object were to talk fast and not to talk sensibly. We are eager to tunnel under

01:49.260 --> 01:55.640
the Atlantic and bring the old world some weeks nearer to the new, but perchance the first news

01:55.640 --> 02:02.440
that will leak through into the broad flapping American ear will be that the Princess Adelaide

02:02.440 --> 02:08.700
has the whooping cough. After all, the man whose horse trots a mile in a minute does not carry the

02:08.700 --> 02:15.520
most important messages. He is not an evangelist, nor does he come round eating locusts and wild

02:15.520 --> 02:25.320
honey. I doubt if flying childrens ever carried a peck of corn to mill. One says to me, I wonder

02:25.320 --> 02:31.620
that you do not lay up money. You love to travel. You might take the cars and go to Fitchburg today

02:31.620 --> 02:39.380
and see the country. But I am wiser than that. I have learned that the swiftest traveler is he

02:39.380 --> 02:46.600
that goes afoot. I say to my friend, suppose we try who will get there first. The distance is

02:46.600 --> 02:54.500
thirty miles, the fare ninety cents. That is almost a day's wages. I remember when wages

02:54.500 --> 03:03.600
were sixty cents a day for laborers on this very road. Well, I start now on foot and get there before

03:03.600 --> 03:12.160
night. I have traveled at that rate by the week together. You will in the meanwhile have earned

03:12.160 --> 03:18.320
your fare and arrive there sometime tomorrow, or possibly this evening if you are lucky enough to

03:18.320 --> 03:24.700
get a job in the season. Instead of going to Fitchburg, you will be working here the greater

03:24.700 --> 03:32.200
part of the day. And so if the railroad reached round the world, I think that I should keep ahead

03:32.200 --> 03:38.500
of you. And as for seeing the country and getting experience of that kind, I should have to cut your

03:38.500 --> 03:46.540
acquaintance altogether. Such is the universal law which no man can ever outwit. And with regard to

03:46.540 --> 03:54.080
railroad, even we may say it is as broad as it is long. To make a railroad round the world available

03:54.080 --> 04:01.620
to all mankind is equivalent to grading the whole surface of the planet. Men have an indistinct notion

04:01.620 --> 04:09.340
that if they keep up this activity of joint stalks and spades long enough, all will at length ride

04:09.340 --> 04:16.960
somewhere in next to no time and for nothing. But though a crowd rushes to the depot and the

04:16.960 --> 04:23.820
conductor shouts, All aboard! when the smoke is blown away and the vapor condensed, it will

04:23.820 --> 04:32.740
be perceived that a few are riding, but the rest are run over, and it will be called and will be

04:33.460 --> 04:41.860
a melancholy accident. No doubt they can ride at last who shall have earned their fare,

04:42.620 --> 04:49.000
that is if they survive so long, but they will probably have lost their elasticity and desire

04:49.000 --> 04:56.040
to travel by that time. This spending of the best part of one's life earning money in order to enjoy

04:56.040 --> 05:03.800
a questionable liberty during the least valuable part of it reminds me of the Englishmen who went

05:03.800 --> 05:10.340
to India to make a fortune first in order that he might return to England and live the life of a poet.

05:11.120 --> 05:18.520
He should have gone up Garrett at once. What? exclaim a million Irishmen starting up from

05:18.520 --> 05:24.440
all the shanties in the land. Is not this railroad which we have built a good thing?

05:25.260 --> 05:33.120
Yes, I answer, comparatively good. That is, you might have done worse. But I wish,

05:33.440 --> 05:39.300
as you are brothers of mine, that you could have spent your time better than digging in this dirt.

05:41.680 --> 05:47.400
Before I finished my house, wishing to earn ten or twelve dollars by some honest and agreeable

05:47.400 --> 05:53.980
method, in order to meet my unusual expenses, I planted about two acres and a half of light

05:53.980 --> 06:01.540
and sandy soil near it chiefly with beans, but also a small part with potatoes, corn, peas,

06:01.920 --> 06:09.480
and turnips. The whole lot contains eleven acres, mostly growing up to pines and hickories,

06:09.720 --> 06:14.520
and was sold the preceding season for eight dollars and eight cents an acre.

06:15.640 --> 06:17.520
One farmer said that it was

06:17.980 --> 06:23.340
quote, good for nothing but to raise cheaping squirrels on, end quote.

06:24.980 --> 06:31.700
I put no manure whatever on this land, not being the owner but merely a squatter, and not expecting

06:31.700 --> 06:44.500
to cultivate so much again, and I did not quite hoe it all at once. I got out several cords of

06:44.500 --> 06:49.980
small circles of virgin mold, easily distinguishable, through the summer by the

06:49.980 --> 06:57.160
greater luxuriance of the beans there. The dead, and for the most part unmerchantable wood behind

06:57.160 --> 07:01.840
my house, and the driftwood from the pond, have supplied the remainder of my fuel.

07:03.360 --> 07:10.020
I was obliged to hire a team and a man for the plowing, though I held the plow myself.

07:10.720 --> 07:19.580
My farm outgoes for the first season were, for implements, seed, work, etc., fourteen dollars

07:19.580 --> 07:27.220
seventy-two cents plus. The seed corn was given me. This never costs anything to speak of,

07:27.600 --> 07:34.620
unless you plant more than enough. I got twelve bushels of beans and eighteen bushels of potatoes

07:34.620 --> 07:41.840
besides some peas and sweet corn. The yellow corn and turnips were too late to come to anything.

07:42.780 --> 07:49.440
The whole income from the farm was twenty-three dollars forty-four cents.

07:50.360 --> 07:58.040
Deducting the outgoes, fourteen dollars seventy-two cents plus, there are left eight dollars

07:58.040 --> 08:05.920
seventy-one cents plus. Beside produce consumed and on hand at the time, this estimate was made

08:05.920 --> 08:14.080
of the value of four dollars fifty cents, the amount on hand much more than balancing a little

08:14.080 --> 08:20.240
grass which I did not raise. All things considered, that is, considering the importance of a man's

08:20.240 --> 08:27.240
soul and of today, notwithstanding the short time occupied by my experiment, nay, partly even

08:27.240 --> 08:33.680
because of its transient character, I believe that was doing better than any farmer in Concord

08:33.680 --> 08:40.340
did that year. The next year I did better still, for I spaded up all the land which I required,

08:40.400 --> 08:46.860
about a third of an acre, and I learned from the experience of both years, not being in the least

08:46.860 --> 08:54.020
awed by many celebrated works on husbandry, Arthur Young among the rest, that if one would live

08:54.020 --> 09:01.200
simply and eat only the crop which he raised, and raise no more than he ate, and not exchange

09:01.200 --> 09:06.540
it for an insufficient quantity of more luxurious and expensive things, he would need to cultivate

09:06.540 --> 09:14.960
only a few rods of ground, and that it would be cheaper to spade up that than to use oxen to plough

09:14.960 --> 09:22.620
it, and to select a fresh spot from time to time than to manure the old, and he could do all his

09:22.620 --> 09:30.820
necessary farm work as it were with his left hand at odd hours in the summer, and thus he would not

09:30.820 --> 09:39.220
be tied to an ox, or horse, or cow, or pig, as at present. I desire to speak impartially on this

09:39.220 --> 09:45.160
point, and as one not interested in the success or failure of the present economical and social

09:45.160 --> 09:52.640
arrangements. I was more independent than any farmer in Concord, for I was not anchored to a

09:52.640 --> 09:59.720
house or farm, but could follow the bent of my genius, which is a very crooked one, every moment.

10:01.600 --> 10:07.360
Beside being better off than they already, if my house had been burned or my crops had failed,

10:07.360 --> 10:16.100
I should have been nearly as well off as before. I am wont to think that men are not so much the

10:16.100 --> 10:24.380
keepers of herds as herds are the keepers of men. The former are so much the freer.

10:25.220 --> 10:33.800
Men and oxen exchange work, but if we consider necessary work only, the oxen will be seen to have

10:33.800 --> 10:41.780
greatly the advantage. Their farm is so much the larger. Man does some of his part of the exchange

10:41.780 --> 10:50.900
work in his six weeks of haying, and it is no boy's play. Certainly no nation that lived simply in all

10:50.900 --> 10:57.960
respects, that is no nation of philosophers, would commit so great a blunder as to use the labor of

10:57.960 --> 11:05.620
animals. True, there never was and is not likely soon to be a nation of philosophers, nor am I

11:05.620 --> 11:11.640
certain it is desirable that there should be. However, I should never have broken a horse or

11:11.640 --> 11:17.620
bull and taken him to board for any work he might do for me, for fear I should become a horseman or

11:17.620 --> 11:26.080
herdsman merely. And if society seems to be the gainer by so doing, are we certain that what is

11:26.080 --> 11:33.140
one man's gain is not another's loss, and that the stable boy has equal cause with his master

11:33.140 --> 11:40.700
to be satisfied? Granted that some public works would not have been constructed without this aid,

11:41.440 --> 11:48.820
and let man share the glory of such with the ox and horse, does it follow that he could not

11:48.820 --> 11:56.360
have accomplished works yet more worthy of himself in that case? When men begin to do

11:56.360 --> 12:06.220
not merely unnecessary or artistic, but luxurious and idle work with their assistance, it is

12:06.220 --> 12:13.860
inevitable that a few do all the exchange work with the oxen, or in other words, become the slaves

12:13.860 --> 12:22.840
of the strongest. Man thus not only works for the animal within him, but, for a symbol of this,

12:23.120 --> 12:31.300
he works for the animal without him. Though we have many substantial houses of brick or stone,

12:31.820 --> 12:38.820
the prosperity of the farmer is still measured by the degree to which the barn overshadows the house.

12:39.770 --> 12:47.600
This town is said to have the largest houses for oxen, cows, and horses hereabouts, and it is not

12:47.600 --> 12:55.820
behind hand in its public buildings, but there are very few halls for free worship or free speech in

12:55.820 --> 13:03.880
this county. It should not be by their architecture, but why not even by their power of abstract

13:03.880 --> 13:12.720
thought that nations should seek to commemorate themselves? How much more admirable the Bhagavad

13:12.720 --> 13:22.080
Gita than all the ruins of the East. Towers and temples are the luxury of princes. A simple and

13:22.080 --> 13:30.260
independent mind does not toil at the bidding of any prince. Genius is not a retainer to any emperor,

13:30.820 --> 13:37.720
nor is its material silver, or gold, or marble, except to a trifling extent.

13:38.740 --> 13:47.700
To what end, pray, is so much stone hammered? In Arcadia, when I was there, I did not see any

13:47.700 --> 14:00.240
hammering stone. Nations are possessed with an insane ambition to perpetuate the memory of

14:00.240 --> 14:06.880
them. What if equal pains were taken to smooth and polish their manners?

14:07.960 --> 14:14.320
One piece of good sense would be more memorable than a monument as high as the moon.

14:15.540 --> 14:24.020
I love better to see stones in place. The grandeur of Thebes was a vulgar grandeur.

14:24.020 --> 14:31.200
More sensible is a rod of stone wall that bounds an honest man's field than a hundred gated Thebes

14:31.200 --> 14:39.430
that has wandered farther from the true end of life. The religion and civilization which are

14:39.840 --> 14:48.900
barbaric and heathenish build splendid temples, but what you might call Christianity does not.

14:49.860 --> 14:59.300
Most of the stone a nation hammers goes towards its tomb only. It buries itself alive.

15:00.340 --> 15:07.720
As for the pyramids, there is nothing to wonder at in them, so much as the fact

15:07.720 --> 15:15.680
that so many men could be found degraded enough to spend their lives constructing a tomb

15:15.680 --> 15:23.780
for some ambitious booby, whom it would have been wiser and manlier to have drowned in the nile

15:23.780 --> 15:30.760
and then given his body to the dogs. I might possibly invent some excuse for them

15:30.760 --> 15:38.780
and him, but I have no time for it. As for the religion and love of art of the builders,

15:39.740 --> 15:46.760
it is much the same all the world over whether the building be an Egyptian temple or the United

15:46.760 --> 15:58.600
States bank. It costs more than it comes to. The main spring is vanity, assisted by the love of

15:58.600 --> 16:08.760
garlic and bread and butter. Mr. Balcombe, a promising young architect, designs it on the

16:08.760 --> 16:15.500
hard pencil and ruler, and the job is led out to dobson and sons stone cutters.

16:16.880 --> 16:23.600
When the thirty centuries begin to look down on it, mankind begin to look up at it.

16:24.480 --> 16:32.100
As for your high towers and monuments, there was a crazy fellow once in this town who undertook to

16:32.100 --> 16:39.180
dig through to China, and he got so far that, as he said, he heard the Chinese pots and kettles

16:39.180 --> 16:45.760
rattle. But I think that I shall not go out of my way to admire the hole which he made.

16:47.300 --> 16:54.040
Many are concerned about the monuments of the West and the East, to know who built them.

16:54.500 --> 17:02.080
For my part I should like to know who in those days did not build them, who were above such

17:02.100 --> 17:11.340
trifling. But to proceed with my statistics. By surveying carpentry and day labor of various

17:11.340 --> 17:18.180
other kinds in the village in the meanwhile, for I have as many trades as fingers, I had earned

17:18.180 --> 17:25.780
thirteen dollars thirty-four cents. The expense of food for eight months, namely from July 4th

17:25.780 --> 17:32.040
to March 1st, the time when these estimates were made, though I lived there more than two years,

17:33.620 --> 17:38.640
not counting potatoes, a little green corn, and some peas which I had raised,

17:39.040 --> 17:48.760
nor considering the value of what was on hand at the last date, was rice one dollar seventy-three

17:48.760 --> 17:59.440
cents and a half. Molasses, one dollar seventy-three cents, cheapest form of the saccharin. Rye meal,

18:00.580 --> 18:08.040
one dollar four cents three quarters. Indian meal, ninety-nine cents three quarters,

18:08.620 --> 18:16.200
cheaper than rye. Pork, twenty-two cents. All experiments which failed.

18:16.960 --> 18:27.420
Flour, eighty-eight cents, costs more than Indian meal, both money and trouble. Sugar, eighty cents.

18:27.960 --> 18:35.180
Lard, sixty-five cents. Apples, twenty-five cents. Dried apple, twenty-two cents.

18:35.180 --> 18:46.900
Sweet potatoes, ten cents. One pumpkin, six cents. One watermelon, two cents. Salt, three cents.

18:47.880 --> 18:56.100
Yes, I did eat eight dollars seventy-four cents, all told. But I should not thus unblushingly

18:56.100 --> 19:01.980
publish my guilt if I did not know that most of my readers were equally guilty with myself,

19:01.980 --> 19:08.060
and that their deeds would look no better in print. The next year I sometimes caught a mess

19:08.060 --> 19:14.920
of fish for my dinner, and once I went so far as to slaughter a woodchuck which ravaged my bean field,

19:15.760 --> 19:23.240
affect his transmigration as a tartar would say, and devour him, partly for experiment's sake.

19:24.100 --> 19:31.960
But though it afforded me a momentary enjoyment, notwithstanding a musky flavor, I saw that the

19:31.960 --> 19:38.560
longest use would not make that a good practice. However, it might seem to have your woodchucks

19:38.560 --> 19:44.920
ready dressed by the village butcher. Clothing and some incidental expenses within the same dates,

19:45.440 --> 19:51.440
though little can be inferred from this item, amounted to eight dollars forty cents minus

19:51.440 --> 19:59.620
three quarters. Oil and some household utensils, two dollars. So that all the pecuniary out goes,

20:00.280 --> 20:05.280
excepting for washing and mending, which for the most part were done out of the house,

20:05.640 --> 20:11.820
and their bills have not yet been received. And these are all, and more than all, the ways by

20:11.820 --> 20:28.600
which money necessarily goes out in this part of the world, were house, twenty-eight dollars

20:28.600 --> 20:36.140
seventy-four cents. Clothing, et cetera, eight months. Eight dollars forty cents minus three

20:36.140 --> 20:45.960
quarters. Oil, et cetera, eight months. Two dollars. In all, sixty-one dollars ninety-nine

20:45.960 --> 20:53.740
cents minus three quarters. I address myself now to those of my readers who have a living to get,

20:53.740 --> 21:00.920
and to meet this I have, for farm produce sold, twenty-three dollars forty-four cents.

21:01.680 --> 21:09.560
Earned by day labor, thirteen dollars thirty-four cents. In all, thirty-six dollars seventy-eight

21:09.560 --> 21:15.980
cents. Which, subtracted from the sum of the out goes, leaves a balance of twenty-five dollars

21:15.980 --> 21:22.420
twenty-one cents three quarters on the one side. This being very nearly the means with which I

21:22.420 --> 21:28.880
started, and the measure of expenses to be incurred. And on the other, beside the leisure

21:28.880 --> 21:36.000
and independence and health thus secured, a comfortable house for me, as long as I chose to

21:36.000 --> 21:43.020
occupy it. These statistics, however accidental and therefore uninstructive they may appear,

21:43.640 --> 21:49.820
as they have a certain completeness, have a certain value also. Nothing was given me of

21:49.820 --> 21:56.480
which I have not rendered some account. It appears from the above estimate that my food

21:56.480 --> 22:03.440
alone cost me in money about twenty-seven cents a week. It was, for nearly two years after this,

22:03.820 --> 22:12.440
rye and Indian meal, without yeast, potatoes, rice, a very little salt pork, molasses, and salt,

22:13.160 --> 22:19.500
and my drink, water. It was fit that I should live on rice, mainly,

22:19.800 --> 22:26.220
who love so well the philosophy of India. To meet the objections of some inveterate

22:26.220 --> 22:33.740
cavalers, I may as well state that if I dined out occasionally, as I always had done,

22:34.380 --> 22:41.220
and I trust shall have opportunities to do again, it was frequently to the detriment of my domestic

22:41.220 --> 22:47.540
arrangements. But the dining out being, as I have stated, a constant element, does not in the least

22:47.540 --> 22:53.640
affect a comparative statement like this. I learned from my two years' experience that it

22:53.640 --> 22:59.200
would cost incredibly little trouble to obtain one's necessary food, even in this latitude,

22:59.760 --> 23:05.820
that a man may use as simple a diet as the animals, and yet retain health and strength.

23:06.540 --> 23:11.020
I have made a satisfactory dinner, satisfactory on several accounts,

23:11.500 --> 23:20.960
simply off a dish of purslane, portulaca oleracea, which I gathered in my cornfield,

23:21.300 --> 23:28.060
boiled and salted. I give the Latin on account of the savouriness of the trivial name,

23:29.020 --> 23:36.580
and pray what more can a reasonable man desire in peaceful times in ordinary noons than a sufficient

23:36.580 --> 23:45.480
number of ears of green sweet corn boiled with the addition of salt. Even the little variety

23:45.480 --> 23:52.930
which I used was a yielding to the demands of appetite, and not of health. Yet men have

23:52.930 --> 24:00.510
such a pass that they frequently starve, not for want of necessaries, but for want of luxuries.

24:01.470 --> 24:07.650
And I know a good woman who thinks that her son lost his life because he took to drinking water

24:07.650 --> 24:14.090
only. The reader will perceive that I am treating the subject rather from an economic

24:14.090 --> 24:20.790
than a dietetic point of view, and he will not venture to put my abstemiousness to the test

24:20.790 --> 24:28.430
unless he has a well-stocked larder. Bread I at first made of pure Indian meal and salt,

24:29.030 --> 24:35.070
genuine hoe-cakes, which I baked before my fire out of doors on a shingle, or the end of a stick

24:35.070 --> 24:42.250
of timber sawed off in building my house. But it was want to get smoked and to have a piney flavour.

24:42.870 --> 24:50.630
I tried flour also, but have at last found a mixture of rye and Indian meal most convenient

24:50.630 --> 24:58.270
and agreeable. In cold weather it was no little amusement to bake several small loaves of this

24:58.270 --> 25:03.610
in succession, tending and turning them as carefully as an Egyptian his hatching eggs.

25:04.490 --> 25:12.830
They were a real cereal fruit which I ripened, and they had to my senses a fragrance like that

25:12.830 --> 25:18.630
of other noble fruits, which I kept in as long as possible by wrapping them in cloths.

25:19.430 --> 25:26.270
I made a study of the ancient and indispensable art of bread-making, consulting such authorities

25:26.270 --> 25:32.810
as offered, going back to the primitive days and first invention of the unleavened kind,

25:33.590 --> 25:40.550
when from the wildness of nuts and meats men first reached the mildness and refinement of this diet,

25:41.790 --> 25:47.490
and travelling gradually down in my studies through the accidental souring of the dough,

25:47.490 --> 25:52.790
which it is supposed taught the leavening process, and through the various fermentations

25:52.790 --> 26:01.230
thereafter, till I came to good, sweet, wholesome bread, the staff of life.

26:02.190 --> 26:11.010
Leaven, which some deem the soul of bread, the spiritus, which fills its cellular tissue,

26:11.010 --> 26:17.810
which is religiously preserved like the Vestal Fire, some precious bottleful, I suppose,

26:18.030 --> 26:23.810
first brought over in the Mayflower, did the business for America, and its influence is still

26:23.810 --> 26:32.930
rising, swelling, spreading in cerealian billows over the land. This seed I regularly and faithfully

26:32.930 --> 26:39.890
procured from the village, till at length, one morning, I forgot the rules and scalded my yeast,

26:39.890 --> 26:46.450
by which accident I discovered that even this was not indispensable, for my discoveries were

26:46.450 --> 26:55.030
not by the synthetic but analytic process, and I have gladly omitted it since, though most housewives

26:55.030 --> 27:02.270
earnestly assured me that safe and wholesome bread without yeast might not be. An elderly

27:02.270 --> 27:08.950
people prophesied a steady decay of the vital forces, yet I find it not to be an essential

27:08.950 --> 27:14.450
ingredient, and after going without it for a year, am still in the land of the living,

27:14.810 --> 27:19.490
and I am glad to escape the trivialness of carrying a bottleful in my pocket,

27:19.950 --> 27:24.090
which would sometimes pop and discharge its contents to my discomfiture.

27:25.150 --> 27:28.390
It is simpler and more respectable to omit it.

27:30.410 --> 27:36.630
Man is an animal who more than any other can adapt himself to all climates and circumstances.

27:37.590 --> 27:43.230
Neither did I put any sal soda or other acid or alkali into my bread.

27:44.230 --> 27:48.210
It would seem that I made it according to the recipe which Marcus

27:48.210 --> 27:52.250
Portius Cato gave about two centuries before Christ.

28:06.630 --> 28:17.370
Palatim adito subigitok pokre, ubi bennei subigeris defingito coquitok sub testu,

28:18.930 --> 28:19.970
which I take to mean,

28:22.250 --> 28:31.230
Make kneaded bread thus. Wash your hands and trough well. Put the meal into the trough,

28:31.230 --> 28:37.950
add water gradually, and knead it thoroughly. When you have kneaded it well,

28:38.570 --> 28:47.310
mold it and bake it under a cover. That is in a baking kettle. Not a word about leaven.

28:48.350 --> 28:56.390
But I did not always use this staff of life. At one time, owing to the emptiness of my purse,

28:56.390 --> 29:04.290
I saw none of it for more than a month. Every New Englander might easily raise all his own

29:04.290 --> 29:11.270
breadstuffs in this land of rye and Indian corn, and not depend on distant and fluctuating markets

29:11.270 --> 29:20.150
for them. Yet so far are we from simplicity and independence that, in Concord, fresh and sweet

29:20.150 --> 29:28.370
meal is rarely sold in the shops, and hominy and corn in a still coarser form are hardly used by

29:28.370 --> 29:36.550
any. For the most part the farmer gives to his cattle and hogs the grain of his own producing,

29:37.210 --> 29:43.830
and buys flour, which is at least no more wholesome, at a greater cost at the store.

29:44.670 --> 29:50.950
I saw that I could easily raise my bushel or two of rye and Indian corn, for the farmer will

29:50.950 --> 29:57.190
grow on the poorest land, and the latter does not require the best, and grind them in a hand-mill,

29:57.430 --> 30:05.490
and so do without rice and pork. And if I must have some concentrated sweet, I found by experiment

30:06.070 --> 30:13.450
that I could make a very good molasses either of pumpkins or beets, and I knew that I needed

30:13.450 --> 30:21.230
only to set out a few maples to obtain it more easily still, and while these were growing I

30:21.230 --> 30:28.830
could use various substitutes beside those which I have named. For, as the forefather sang,

30:30.890 --> 30:37.710
we can make liquor to sweeten our lips of pumpkins and parsnips and walnut-tree chips.

30:39.470 --> 30:46.010
Finally, as for salt, that grossest of groceries, to obtain this might be a

30:46.010 --> 30:51.790
fit occasion for a visit to the seashore, or, if I did without it altogether,

30:52.050 --> 30:58.650
I should probably drink the less water. I do not learn that the Indians ever troubled themselves

30:58.650 --> 31:05.450
to go after it. Thus I could avoid all trade and barter, so far as my food was concerned,

31:05.450 --> 31:10.090
and having a shelter already, it would only remain to get clothing and fuel.

31:10.990 --> 31:17.530
The pantaloons which I now wear were woven in a farmer's family. Thank heaven there is so much

31:17.530 --> 31:24.810
virtue still in man, for I think the fall from the farmer to the operative as great and memorable as

31:24.810 --> 31:33.070
that from the man to the farmer, and in a new country fuel is an encumbrance. As for a habitat,

31:33.070 --> 31:39.290
if I were not permitted still to squat, I might purchase one acre at the same price for which the

31:39.290 --> 31:47.190
land I cultivated was sold, namely eight dollars and eight cents. But as it was, I considered that I

31:47.190 --> 31:54.290
enhanced the value of the land by squatting on it. There is a certain class of unbelievers

31:54.290 --> 32:00.330
who sometimes ask me such questions as, if I think that I can live on vegetable food alone,

32:00.330 --> 32:06.910
and to strike at the root of the matter at once, for the root is faith, I am accustomed to answer

32:06.910 --> 32:14.750
such that I can live on bored nails. If they cannot understand that, they cannot understand much

32:14.750 --> 32:20.970
that I have to say. For my part I am glad to bear of experiments of this kind being tried,

32:21.830 --> 32:28.470
as that a young man tried for a fortnight to live on hard raw corn on the ear, using his teeth for

32:28.470 --> 32:34.730
mortar. The squirrel tribe tried the same and succeeded. The human race is interested in these

32:34.730 --> 32:40.970
experiments, though a few old women who are incapacitated for them, or who own their thirds

32:40.970 --> 32:50.290
in mills, may be alarmed. My furniture, part of which I made myself, and the rest cost me nothing

32:50.290 --> 32:59.430
of which I have not rendered an account, consisted of a bed, a table, a desk, three chairs, a looking

32:59.430 --> 33:07.410
glass three inches in diameter, a pair of tongs and and irons, a kettle, a skillet, and a frying pan,

33:07.930 --> 33:17.010
a dipper, a wash bowl, two knives and forks, three plates, one cup, one spoon, a jug for oil,

33:17.010 --> 33:24.710
a jug for molasses, and a Japan lamp. None is so poor that he need to sit on a pumpkin.

33:25.730 --> 33:31.910
That is shiftlessness. There is a plenty of such chairs as I like best in the village

33:31.910 --> 33:39.910
Gerrits to be had for taking them away. Furniture. Thank God I can sit and I can stand without the aid

33:39.910 --> 33:47.690
of a furniture warehouse. What man but a philosopher would not be ashamed to see his

33:47.690 --> 33:53.230
furniture packed in a cart and going upcountry exposed to the light of heaven in the eyes of

33:53.230 --> 34:02.730
men? A beggarly account of empty boxes. That is Spalding's furniture. I could never tell

34:02.730 --> 34:09.890
from inspecting such a load whether it belonged to a so-called rich man or a poor one. The owner

34:09.890 --> 34:17.030
always seemed poverty-stricken. Indeed, the more you have of such things, the poorer you are.

34:17.690 --> 34:25.170
Each load looks as if it contained the contents of a dozen shanties, and if one shanty is poor,

34:25.750 --> 34:34.030
this is a dozen times as poor. Pray, for what do we move ever but to get rid of our furniture,

34:34.030 --> 34:41.990
our exuviae, at last to go from this world to another newly furnished and leave this to be

34:41.990 --> 34:50.490
burned? It is the same as if all these traps were buckled to a man's belt and he could not move over

34:50.490 --> 34:56.230
the rough country where our lines are cast without dragging them, dragging his trap.

34:57.190 --> 35:05.070
He was a lucky fox that left his tail in the trap. The muskrat will gnaw his third leg

35:05.070 --> 35:14.470
off to be free. No wonder man has lost his elasticity. How often he is at a dead set.

35:15.950 --> 35:21.250
Sir, if I may be so bold, what do you mean by a dead set?

35:23.550 --> 35:30.510
If you are a seer, whenever you meet a man, you will see all that he owns,

35:30.990 --> 35:37.310
I and much that he pretends to disown, behind him, even to his kitchen furniture,

35:37.510 --> 35:44.750
and all the trumpery which he saves and will not burn, and he will appear to be harnessed to it,

35:44.750 --> 35:53.910
and making what headway he can. I think that the man is at a dead set, who has got through

35:53.910 --> 36:00.570
a knothole or gateway where his sledge load of furniture cannot follow him.

36:01.410 --> 36:05.610
I cannot but feel compassion when I hear some trim, compact-looking man,

36:05.630 --> 36:14.410
seemingly free, all girded and ready, speak of his furniture, as whether it is insured or not.

36:14.750 --> 36:22.130
But what shall I do with my furniture? My gay butterfly is entangled in a spider's web then.

36:22.890 --> 36:28.790
Even those who seem for a long while not to have any, if you inquire more narrowly,

36:29.010 --> 36:36.270
you will find have some stored in somebody's barn. I look upon England to-day as an old gentleman

36:36.270 --> 36:43.010
who is travelling with a great deal of baggage, trumpery which has accumulated from long

36:43.010 --> 36:50.690
which he has not the courage to burn, great trunk, little trunk, band box, and bundle.

36:51.430 --> 36:58.410
Throw away the first three at least. It would surpass the powers of a well man nowadays

36:58.410 --> 37:05.530
to take up his bed and walk, and I should certainly advise a sick one to lay down his bed and run.

37:06.430 --> 37:11.010
When I have met an immigrant tottering under a bundle which contained his all,

37:11.010 --> 37:18.690
looking like an enormous wen which had grown out of the nape of his neck, I have pitied him,

37:18.690 --> 37:25.890
not because that was his all, but because he had all that to carry. If I have got to drag

37:25.890 --> 37:32.070
my trap I will take care that it be a light one and do not nip me in a vital part,

37:32.970 --> 37:39.550
but perchance it would be wisest never to put one's paw into it. I would observe, by the way,

37:39.550 --> 37:46.490
that it costs me nothing for curtains, for I have no gazers to shut out but the sun and moon,

37:46.810 --> 37:54.450
and I am willing that they should look in. The moon will not sour milk nor taint meat of mine,

37:55.010 --> 38:02.050
nor will the sun injure my furniture or fade my carpet, and if he is sometimes too warm a friend,

38:02.590 --> 38:07.950
I find it still better economy to retreat behind some curtain which nature has provided

38:07.950 --> 38:12.210
than to add a single item to the details of my housekeeping.

38:13.470 --> 38:20.010
A lady once offered me a mat, but as I had no room to spare within the house,

38:20.550 --> 38:26.770
nor time to spare within or without to shake it, I declined it, preferring to wipe my feet on the

38:26.770 --> 38:35.230
sod before my door. It is best to avoid the beginnings of evil. Not long since I was present

38:35.230 --> 38:40.830
at the auction of a deacon's effects, for his life had not been ineffectual.

38:42.370 --> 38:45.630
The evil that men do lives after them.

38:47.130 --> 38:52.810
As usual, a great proportion was trumpery which had begun to accumulate in his father's day.

38:53.470 --> 39:00.590
Among the rest was a dried tapeworm. And now, after lying half a century in his

39:01.210 --> 39:09.570
dust-holes, these things were not burned. Instead of a bonfire or purifying destruction of them,

39:10.130 --> 39:17.670
there was an auction, or increasing of them. The neighbors eagerly collected to view them,

39:18.110 --> 39:24.570
bought them all, and carefully transported them to their garrets and dust-holes to lie there till

39:24.570 --> 39:31.050
their estates are settled, when they will start again, when a man dies he kicks the dust.

39:32.070 --> 39:37.170
The customs of some savage nations might perchance be profitably imitated by us,

39:37.830 --> 39:43.470
for they at least go through the semblance of casting their slough annually. They have

39:43.470 --> 39:50.150
the idea of the thing, whether they have the reality or not. Would it not be well if we were

39:50.150 --> 39:57.570
to celebrate such a busk, or feast of first fruits, as Bartram describes to have been the

39:57.570 --> 40:05.650
custom of the muck-class Indians? When a town celebrates the busk, says he,

40:06.870 --> 40:12.250
Having previously provided themselves with new cloths, new pots, pans, and other household

40:12.250 --> 40:17.350
utensils and furniture, they collect all their worn-out clothes and other despicable things,

40:17.350 --> 40:21.770
sweep and cleanse their houses, squares, and the whole town of their filth,

40:22.510 --> 40:27.910
which with all the remaining grain and other old provisions they cast together into one common heap

40:27.910 --> 40:34.450
and consume it with fire. After having taken medicine and fasted for three days, all the fire

40:34.450 --> 40:41.570
in the town is extinguished. During this fast they abstain from the gratification of every appetite

40:41.570 --> 40:48.010
and passion whatever. A general amnesty is proclaimed. All malefactors may return to their

40:48.010 --> 40:54.250
town. On the fourth morning the high priest, by rubbing dry wood together, produces new fire in

40:54.250 --> 41:00.310
the public square, from whence every habitation in the town is supplied with the new and pure flame.

41:01.790 --> 41:07.530
They then feast on the new corn and fruits, and dance and sing for three days.

41:08.170 --> 41:14.350
And the four following days they receive visits and rejoice with their friends from

41:14.350 --> 41:18.270
neighboring towns who have in like manner purified and prepared themselves.

41:20.230 --> 41:25.210
The Mexicans also practiced a similar purification at the end of every 52 years

41:25.210 --> 41:28.870
in the belief that it was time for the world to come to an end.

41:29.770 --> 41:35.590
I have scarcely heard of a truer sacrament. That is, as the dictionary defines it,

41:35.590 --> 41:42.850
quote, outward and visible sign of an inward and spiritual grace, end quote, than this.

41:43.370 --> 41:48.670
And I have no doubt that they were originally inspired directly from heaven to do thus,

41:49.150 --> 41:51.910
though they have no biblical record of the revelation.

41:53.170 --> 41:58.270
For more than five years I maintained myself thus solely by the labor of my hands,

41:58.270 --> 42:04.070
and I found that by working about six weeks in a year I could meet all the expenses of living.

42:04.710 --> 42:09.810
The whole of my winters, as well as most of my summers, I had free and clear for study.

42:10.790 --> 42:17.510
I have thoroughly tried school-keeping, and found that my expenses were in proportion, or rather out

42:17.510 --> 42:25.270
of proportion, to my income, for I was obliged to dress and train, not to say think and believe

42:25.270 --> 42:31.810
accordingly, and I lost my time into the bargain. As I did not teach for the good of my fellow men,

42:31.810 --> 42:40.070
but simply for a livelihood, this was a failure. I have tried trade, but I found that it would take

42:40.070 --> 42:46.490
ten years to get under way in that, and that then I should probably be on my way to the devil.

42:47.150 --> 42:53.730
I was actually afraid that I might by that time be doing what is called a good business.

42:54.730 --> 42:58.890
When formerly I was looking about to see what I could do for a living,

42:58.890 --> 43:06.810
some sad experience in conforming to the wishes of friends being fresh in my mind to tax my ingenuity,

43:07.830 --> 43:15.230
I thought often and seriously of picking huckleberries. That surely I could do,

43:15.690 --> 43:22.550
and its small profits might suffice, for my greatest skill has been to want but little.

43:23.210 --> 43:28.330
So little capital it required, so little distraction from my wanted moods,

43:28.330 --> 43:34.870
I foolishly thought. While my acquaintances went unhesitatingly into trade or the professions,

43:35.410 --> 43:43.470
I contemplated this occupation as most like theirs, ranging the hills all summer

43:43.470 --> 43:49.670
to pick the berries which came in my way, and thereafter carelessly dispose of them,

43:49.670 --> 43:57.270
so to keep the flocks of ad metis. I also dreamed that I might gather the wild herbs,

43:57.890 --> 44:03.910
or carry evergreens to such villagers as love to be reminded of the woods, even to the city by

44:04.310 --> 44:12.390
hay cart loads. But I have since learned that trade curses everything it handles,

44:13.090 --> 44:19.590
and though you trade in messages from heaven, the whole curse of trade attaches to the business.

44:20.550 --> 44:24.530
As I preferred some things to others, and especially valued my freedom,

44:24.990 --> 44:31.130
as I could fare hard and yet succeed well, I did not wish to spend my time in earning

44:31.130 --> 44:37.830
rich carpets or other fine furniture, or delicate cookery, or a house in the Grecian,

44:37.890 --> 44:44.930
or the Gothic style just yet. If there are any to whom it is no interruption to acquire these things,

44:44.930 --> 44:50.790
and who know how to use them when acquired, I relinquish to them the pursuit.

44:51.870 --> 44:59.190
Some are industrious, and appear to love labor for its own sake, or perhaps because it

44:59.190 --> 45:04.430
keeps them out of worse mischief. To such I have at present nothing to say.

45:05.390 --> 45:10.150
Those who would not know what to do with more leisure than they now enjoy,

45:10.150 --> 45:16.110
I might advise to work twice as hard as they do, work till they pay for themselves,

45:16.190 --> 45:23.390
and get their free papers. For myself I found that the occupation of a day laborer was the

45:23.390 --> 45:29.030
most independent of any, especially as it required only thirty or forty days in a year to support one.

45:29.990 --> 45:36.170
The laborer's day ends with the going down of the sun, and he is then free to devote himself

45:36.170 --> 45:42.770
to his chosen pursuit, independent of his labor, but his employer, who speculates from month to

45:42.770 --> 45:50.970
month, has no respite from one end of the year to the other. In short, I am convinced, both by faith

45:50.970 --> 45:58.350
and experience, that to maintain oneself on this earth is not a hardship, but a pastime.

45:58.860 --> 46:06.010
If we will live simply and wisely, as the pursuits of the simpler nations are still

46:06.010 --> 46:12.370
the sports of the more artificial, it is not necessary that a man should earn his

46:12.370 --> 46:21.590
living by the sweat of his brow, unless he sweats easier than I do. End of LibriVox Part 4 of Economy.

